{
  "description": "A simple network performance line chart showing page load time by geographic region. Title: \"Page Load Time by Region\". X-axis labeled \"Region\" with categories: North America, Europe, South America, Asia-Pacific. Y-axis labeled \"Average Load Time (seconds)\" from 0 to 8. Use one series named \"Average page load time\" with example values: North America 1.8, Europe 2.1, South America 6.7, Asia-Pacific 2.4. Highlight South America in a contrasting red color to show it is the only outlier, while the other regions stay clustered around 2 seconds. Add a subtle note beneath the chart: \"Servers healthy; CPU normal; slowdown isolated to one region.\"",
  "kind": "chart"
}

{
  "description": "Tabela de diagnóstico de pedidos de crédito com 4 colunas: \"Pedido\", \"Score de risco\", \"Decisão do sistema\" e \"Alerta\". Mostrar 8 linhas com dados inconsistentes e contrastantes, por exemplo: 1) Pedido A-102 / 0,98 / Aprovado / \"Risco alto ignorado\"; 2) Pedido A-103 / vazio / Não avaliável / \"Falha no score\"; 3) Pedido A-104 / -12,4 / Aprovado / \"Valor fora da faixa\"; 4) Pedido A-105 / 0,72 / Bloqueado / \"OK\"; 5) Pedido A-106 / 1,35 / Aprovado / \"Score inválido\"; 6) Pedido A-107 / 0,00 / Não avaliável / \"Campo ausente\"; 7) Pedido A-108 / 0,89 / Bloqueado / \"Decisão contraditória\"; 8) Pedido A-109 / nulo / Aprovado / \"Sem cálculo\". Destacar visualmente células vazias, valores impossíveis e avisos conflitantes com ícones de alerta vermelhos.",
  "kind": "table"
}

{
  "description": "Gráfico de línea con dos series comparando el rendimiento del lote a lo largo de 5 etapas del proceso. Eje X: 'Etapa del proceso' con puntos 'Recepción', 'Preparación', 'Reacción', 'Filtrado', 'Producto final'. Eje Y: 'Porcentaje'. Serie 1 'Producto útil' baja de 92% en Recepción a 88% en Preparación, 61% en Reacción, 34% en Filtrado y 18% en Producto final. Serie 2 'Impurezas' sube de 4% a 7%, 26%, 41% y 57% en las mismas etapas. Añadir una tercera serie tenue 'Compuestos inesperados' que aparece casi en cero al inicio y salta a 2%, 11%, 19% y 23% desde Reacción en adelante. Resaltar visualmente el punto de quiebre en 'Reacción' con una anotación: 'Aquí se desvió el proceso'.",
  "kind": "chart"
}

{
  "description": "A clean business analytics chart showing the retail chain’s performance from January to October. Use a two-series line chart with the x-axis labeled “Month” (Jan, Feb, Mar, Apr, May, Jun, Jul, Aug, Sep, Oct). The left y-axis should be labeled “Sales Index” and the right y-axis “Inventory Index” or use a single normalized index from 0 to 120. Plot one line for “Total Sales” that rises strongly in the first half of the year, peaking around June at about 115, then declines steadily through October to about 78. Plot a second line for “Inventory on Hand” that stays moderate early in the year around 60–70, then climbs after July and reaches about 110 by October. Add a third marker or bar series for “New Store Target Attainment” averaged across the 18 new stores, starting near 105% in spring, slipping below 100% in July, and ending around 72% by October. Include a subtle annotation around August–October reading “New locations underperforming despite promising markets.” The overall visual should emphasize the divergence: sales falling while inventory rises, and the new stores missing targets in late summer and fall.",
  "kind": "chart"
}

{
  "description": "Diagrama de fluxo do checkout em e-commerce, em português, mostrando uma sequência de etapas conectadas por setas: 'Carrinho' -> 'Dados de entrega' -> 'Pagamento' -> 'Revisão final' -> 'Confirmação'. Destacar visualmente três pontos de falha com ícones de alerta vermelhos nas transições entre 'Dados de entrega' e 'Pagamento', e entre 'Pagamento' e 'Revisão final', além de um pequeno loop de retrabalho de volta para 'Dados de entrega'. Incluir anotações curtas ao lado dos pontos críticos: 'erro aumenta aqui', 'ajuste parcial conserta uma etapa', 'impacta etapas seguintes'. O estilo deve sugerir um sistema em produção, com caminhos principais em azul e caminhos problemáticos em vermelho, sem mostrar interface de tela.",
  "kind": "diagram"
}

{
  "description": "A clean multi-panel diagram showing the national vaccination supply chain and delay points. Center panel: a map silhouette of the country with five region boxes labeled 'North', 'South', 'East', 'West', and 'Central', each connected by arrows to a main 'National Vaccine Hub' at the top. Use thick arrows to indicate vaccine shipments flowing from 'Import Port' -> 'National Warehouse' -> 'Regional Depots' -> 'Local Clinics'. Add small warning icons on the arrows between National Warehouse and some regions to show late deliveries. Annotate two regions as 'Waiting for doses' with dashed outline boxes and two regions as 'Received late' with clock icons. Include a side panel labeled 'Bottlenecks' listing 'Delayed customs clearance', 'Limited refrigerated trucks', and 'Uneven regional allocation'. Keep the layout simple, structured, and analytical, with directional arrows, labels, and highlighted delay nodes to explain why the rollout fell behind schedule.",
  "kind": "diagram"
}

{
  "description": "A realistic image of the exterior of a century-old stone building, viewed from street level at a slight angle so the upper floors are visible. Show several fresh, thin cracks on the upper masonry near window corners and along mortar joints, with the cracks concentrated above mid-height rather than at the base. The stone should look weathered but intact, with no signs of recent renovation such as new brickwork or scaffolding. Include neighboring older buildings in the background that appear visually sound and free of cracks to suggest the issue is isolated to this building. Daylight, documentary style, natural colors, no people, no labels.",
  "kind": "image"
}

{
  "description": "Diagram of the network path from a user in the slow region to the web app, showing a normal path and a slower path side by side. On the left, a user icon labeled \"Slow region users\" connects to \"Regional ISP\" then directly to \"App servers\". On the right, the observed slow route includes extra labeled hops: \"Regional ISP\" -> \"Transit node A\" -> \"Other city\" -> \"Transit node B\" -> \"App servers\". Add callout text noting \"Same hop count on repeated tests\" and \"Delay varies by several seconds between tests\". Use arrows to show packet flow and highlight the detour through the other city in a contrasting color.",
  "kind": "diagram"
}

{
  "description": "Diagrama de fluxo de dados de um sistema de risco de fintech, mostrando uma linha de processamento da esquerda para a direita com etapas nomeadas em português: 'Leitura inicial', 'Normalização de colunas', 'Etapa intermediária', 'Cálculo de risco', 'Fechamento do relatório'. Use três linhas de exemplo para contrastar o comportamento: (1) 'coluna A' entra como '12,5' e 'coluna B' como '12.5', evidenciando diferenças de formato entre colunas parecidas logo na leitura; (2) um campo vazio entra como 'vazio' e na etapa intermediária vira '0' ou '0,0', representando a conversão indevida de vazio em número comum; (3) outra linha mantém o valor original '—' ou 'em branco' até quase o fim e só no fechamento do relatório aparece como '0' ou 'N/A', mostrando que o problema surge apenas no final. Indicar com setas e pequenos alertas vermelhos onde surgem as inconsistências, e com marcações verdes onde o valor original permanece visível por mais tempo. O visual deve enfatizar a transformação inconsistente dos dados ao longo do pipeline, não a interface do sistema.",
  "kind": "diagram"
}

{
  "description": "Diagrama de flujo químico del proceso con el compuesto de partida al inicio y una bifurcación temprana en dos rutas muy parecidas, etiquetadas como “Variante A” y “Variante B” por dos posiciones alternativas de cambio en la molécula. Mostrar un historial del proceso con tres corridas buenas y una corrida mala. En las corridas buenas, la proporción A:B se mantiene baja y estable, por ejemplo 8:6, 7:5 y 9:7, mientras que en la corrida mala aparece mucho más desordenada, por ejemplo 14:3, indicando una desviación en la selectividad. Incluir flechas hacia los productos finales: “producto útil” en una rama y “impurezas / subproductos” en otra, destacando que en la corrida fallida la rama de impurezas domina y la mezcla de variantes se vuelve irregular.",
  "kind": "diagram"
}

{
  "description": "Chart with a monthly time series and grouped comparison by city/region. Use two panels: left panel shows overall sales index from January to October with a strong rise in February–May, an early peak in June, then a steady decline into September–October. Annotate two drivers on the rise: a callout labeled \"holiday shift pulled seasonal purchases earlier\" around March–April, and another labeled \"temporary foot-traffic spike\" around May–June. Right panel shows a scatter or grouped bar comparison of 6 cities: each city has two bars, \"first-half boost\" and \"late-summer retention\". Example values: City A 42 then 39, City B 38 then 35, City C 35 then 33, City D 30 then 18, City E 28 then 16, City F 25 then 14. Highlight that the cities with the largest first-half boosts still remained relatively steady into midsummer before falling later, while others dropped sooner. Use a clear retail dashboard style with axes labeled \"Month\", \"Sales Index\", \"City\", and \"Performance\".",
  "kind": "chart"
}

{
  "description": "Diagrama de fluxo em português mostrando a jornada de um pedido em um sistema de e-commerce com múltiplas etapas e fontes de consulta. À esquerda, um nó \"Pedido criado\" alimenta dois caminhos paralelos: \"Tela do cliente\" e \"Consulta interna/relatório\". Em vários pontos após eventos como \"Pagamento autorizado\", \"Separação\", \"Envio\" e \"Confirmação\", adicionar um destaque visual de inconsistência temporária: por alguns minutos, um caminho mostra \"Concluído\" enquanto o outro mostra \"Pendente\" para o mesmo pedido. Representar isso com setas tracejadas e um relógio pequeno ao lado indicando atraso de sincronização. Na parte inferior, incluir um segundo exemplo separado, rotulado \"Pedido com erro\", onde todas as visões — \"Tela do cliente\", \"API\", \"Consulta administrativa\" — mostram o mesmo status do início ao fim, por exemplo \"Erro\" em todas as caixas, sem divergência. Visual limpo, com caixas retangulares, cores diferentes para status (verde para concluído, amarelo para pendente, vermelho para erro) e uma legenda curta explicando \"diferença temporária entre visões\" versus \"erro consistente em todas as visões\".",
  "kind": "diagram"
}

{
  "description": "Diagram of the vaccine supply and approval chain in the country, showing a left-to-right flow with labeled nodes: \"Regional Health Office\", \"Provincial Office\", \"National Logistics Center\", \"Paperwork Review\", \"Equipment Request Desk\", \"Factory\", and \"Clinic\". Use arrows to show samples, paperwork, and equipment requests traveling through multiple offices before reaching factories or clinics. Add side arrows for \"Urgent Message\" routed directly to \"Same-day Response\" from the national center, highlighting exceptions. Include a dashed bypass path labeled \"Materials Delivered Before Full Reporting Trail\" going straight to certain regions, with a note that reporting was completed afterward. Visually emphasize bottlenecks at the paperwork review and logistics center with thicker, darker arrows and small queue icons.",
  "kind": "diagram"
}

{
  "description": "Diagram showing the relationship between new store launches, competitor activity, and sales performance. Center the diagram on 18 new-store cities split into two groups: 7 cities with a nearby competitor change and 11 cities with no major competitor change. Use two parallel branches from a left-side node labeled \"18 New Store Cities\". Top branch: \"7 cities\" leading to a node labeled \"Competitor changed within weeks of launch\" with two sublabels: \"new competitor location\" and \"heavy discounting.\" Bottom branch: \"11 cities\" leading to a node labeled \"No major competitor change on record.\" On the right side, both branches point to a common outcome node labeled \"Similar sales slide over same period\" and a final node below it labeled \"Inventory buildup / targets missed.\" Use arrows to show that both groups experienced the same decline, emphasizing that competitor pressure explains only part of the pattern. Keep the design clean, business-like, with muted colors and clear labels.",
  "kind": "diagram"
}

{
  "description": "Chart with a horizontal stacked timing bar comparison for two user regions: \"Healthy region\" and \"Affected region\". Each row shows the same page load phases in order: \"DNS + connect\" (very short, about 80 ms in both), \"Server starts response\" (about 220 ms in both), \"First response bytes received\" marker, then a long \"Data exchange / response streaming\" segment. In the healthy region, the post-first-byte data exchange is short, about 300 ms, and total load time is around 520 ms. In the affected region, the post-first-byte data exchange is much longer, about 3.8 s, making total load time about 4.1 s. Visually emphasize that the large gap happens after the first bytes arrive, not before them. Use clear labels on each phase and a note at the bottom: \"Server CPU remains normal; slowdown is concentrated in network/data transfer after response begins.\"",
  "kind": "chart"
}

{
  "description": "A two-panel network performance diagram. Left panel shows a map-like path from a user region to the app servers through a network route, with highlighted points labeled \"ISP / transit hop\" and \"edge router.\" Along the path, annotate \"bursts of dropped packets\" with red packet icons falling away, and a counter labeled \"delayed retransmissions\" rising over time (for example 5, 18, 34, 52). Right panel shows a simplified timeline comparison for the same hours: one line for \"packet drops\" that spikes intermittently, and one line for \"page load time\" that stays high even during stretches where drops are near zero. Include a note near the bottom: \"Slow loads persist even when drops are absent, suggesting more than one network issue or an upstream latency problem.\" Use clear arrows, small labels, and a clean investigative style.",
  "kind": "diagram"
}

{
  "description": "Chart showing page load time by test location and page size. Use a clustered bar chart with the x-axis labeled 'Test location' and the y-axis labeled 'Page load time (seconds)'. Include five locations: 'Local city 1', 'Local city 2', 'Nearby region city', 'Distant region city', and 'Global baseline'. For each location, show two bars: 'Small page' and 'Large page'. Example values: Local city 1: 2.4s small, 6.8s large; Local city 2: 2.6s small, 7.1s large; Nearby region city: 2.1s small, 6.5s large; Distant region city: 1.9s small, 2.4s large; Global baseline: 2.0s small, 2.6s large. Add a horizontal reference line at 2.5s for normal load time. Visually emphasize that nearby locations are several seconds slower, the requests still complete, and the gap is much larger for large pages than small pages.",
  "kind": "chart"
}

{
  "description": "A line chart with a time axis labeled \"Time\" and a y-axis labeled \"Value\" showing two series: \"App Server CPU (%)\" staying flat around 35–45% throughout the slowdown window, and \"App Server Request Queue (requests)\" mostly near 0–2 but briefly spiking to about 18–22 for a short interval near the middle of the chart before returning to baseline. Add a third faint reference series \"Response Time (ms)\" hovering close to its usual baseline around 120–160 ms, with no major increase. Annotate the spike period with a note: \"Brief queue buildup; unaffected regions still loading normally.\" The overall visual should emphasize that the server appears healthy, with only a short-lived queue increase rather than sustained overload.",
  "kind": "chart"
}

{
  "description": "An annotated architectural close-up image of an old stone building’s upper-floor interior wall beneath a row of windows. Show several fresh diagonal cracks starting at the top corners of window frames and extending upward toward the ceiling at about 30–45 degrees. The new cracks should have sharp edges with bright, light-colored exposed stone inside the fractures, clearly lacking dark staining, dust buildup, or weathering. On the same wall, include a few thinner older hairline cracks with similar diagonal direction, but make them look faint and stable-looking, slightly darker or blended into the aged wall surface. Use callout labels or subtle markers to distinguish 'new cracks' from 'older stable cracks.' The setting should feel like a century-old masonry interior: rough stone blocks, mortar joints, and aged plaster, with the cracks concentrated on upper floors near windows.",
  "kind": "image"
}

{
  "description": "Image of the exterior foundation of a century-old stone building, shown as a side-by-side comparison of the east and west sides. On the east side, depict a dark damp band running continuously along the base of the exposed foundation, about 1 foot high, with visible soft powdery erosion patches and slightly rough, weakened stone texture. On the west side, show only a few smaller damp patches lower on the foundation, with the stone surface looking intact, firm, and more solid. Keep the focus on material condition and moisture patterns, with no people, labels, or interior details.",
  "kind": "image"
}

{
  "description": "Image of a century-old stone building wall section shown in elevation, focused on the same structural bay spanning basement, ground floor, third floor, and fourth floor. Depict the basement and ground-floor mortar as intact, tight, and solid in color, with stones firmly bonded and no visible gaps. Above, on the third and fourth floors, show deteriorated mortar joints that look sandy and friable, with crumbly edges, small chunks missing, and several open gaps large enough to fit a fingertip between stones. Emphasize the vertical contrast: lower levels appear sound while upper levels show clear mortar decay and separation. Include subtle crack lines near the weakened upper joints.",
  "kind": "image"
}

{
  "description": "Image of the east exterior wall of a century-old stone building, shown in a realistic inspection view. The roofline gutter above the east wall has a subtle leak point or overflow area. A broad vertical band of discolored stone runs from the gutter down several stories: the stone is darker, stained brown-gray, with pale white mineral deposits and streaking concentrated along the path of runoff. At the base of the east wall, the soil is noticeably darker and wetter than the other sides, with damp patches and slightly muddy ground even though the rest of the scene looks dry. Include a comparison feel by showing the north side only in the background or as a small inset with clean, unstained stone and drier soil. Emphasize that the interior condition is not severe: no obvious interior damage, only a faint moisture meter indication on the east wall compared with a normal reading on the north wall.",
  "kind": "image"
}
